// A generic free function called with EXPLICIT turbofish type arguments
// (`id<i64>(..)`, `id<bool>(..)`) monomorphises and runs at two distinct
// BitCopy types in one program. Before the checker recorded turbofish sites in
// `call_type_args`, an explicit-`<T>` call produced no monomorphisation entry,
// so MIR found no per-instantiation symbol and failed closed with
// "MIR lowering for function call is not implemented yet". Recording at every
// generic call site (turbofish or inferred) registers `id$$i64` / `id$$bool`
// so MIR has a concrete body to dispatch to.
//
// `wrap<i64>(..)` additionally drives a turbofish call whose argument is the
// enclosing fn's own type parameter (`id<U>(x)` inside `wrap<U>`): the abstract
// arg `U` is recorded and resolved per-monomorphisation, proving the
// enclosing-type-param surface routes through the same machinery.
fn id<T>(x: T) -> T {
    x
}

fn wrap<U>(x: U) -> U {
    id<U>(x)
}

fn main() {
    println(id<i64>(5));
    println(id<bool>(true));
    println(wrap<i64>(7));
}
